  <sec sec-type="intro" id="SEC1">
    <title>Introduction</title>
    <p>The interactions between tumor cells and the tumor microenvironment (TME) play crucial roles in cancer initiation, progression and metastasis (<xref rid="B1" ref-type="bibr">1–3</xref>). The diverse types of cells in the TME are organized in a highly structured manner to facilitate efficient functions, particularly within tumor tissues (<xref rid="B4" ref-type="bibr">4</xref>,<xref rid="B5" ref-type="bibr">5</xref>). Traditional bulk RNA sequencing and prevalent single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNA-seq) methods (<xref rid="B6" ref-type="bibr">6</xref>), however, disrupt this cellular organization and do not provide spatial information. In contrast, the emergence of spatial transcriptomics offers a high-resolution perspective of the tumor landscape (<xref rid="B7" ref-type="bibr">7</xref>,<xref rid="B8" ref-type="bibr">8</xref>), shedding light on the complex interactions between cancer cells, immune cells, stromal cells and the extracellular matrix.</p>
    <p>Recently, a variety of spatial omics technologies have been developed, including sequencing-based and imaging-based technologies. Sequencing-based technology captures and preserves spatial expression information by <italic toggle="yes">in situ</italic> hybridization of RNA transcripts onto a fixed spatial index, as seen in 10× visium (<xref rid="B9" ref-type="bibr">9</xref>), spatial transcriptomics (ST) (<xref rid="B10" ref-type="bibr">10</xref>) and Slide-seq (<xref rid="B11" ref-type="bibr">11</xref>). These technologies have advanced the field of spatial transcriptome, especially in the context of human diseases (<xref rid="B12" ref-type="bibr">12–14</xref>). However, the influx of spatial transcriptomics data also presents challenges. Diverse and complex data formats increase the difficulty for most biologists and require more time and effort to process and utilize. Furthermore, each spot in tissue slices contains multiple cells, emphasizing the importance of integrating scRNA-seq data in the analysis (<xref rid="B6" ref-type="bibr">6</xref>,<xref rid="B15" ref-type="bibr">15</xref>). Unfortunately, there are no matched scRNA-seq data for most available spatial transcriptomics datasets in cancer.</p>
    <p>Currently available spatial transcriptomics data are mainly generated by sequencing-based technology. Several databases have been constructed to visualize and analyze the wealth of data generated by spatial omics technologies. For instance, SpatialDB (<xref rid="B16" ref-type="bibr">16</xref>) and Spacer (<xref rid="B17" ref-type="bibr">17</xref>) mainly provided spatial omics dataset storage, querying and visualization of slices. Their usability is limited by a lack of interactive tools and cancer types. Aquila (<xref rid="B18" ref-type="bibr">18</xref>) and SODB (<xref rid="B19" ref-type="bibr">19</xref>) have developed several basic downstream functionality and interactive modules. However, only a limited number of spatial transcriptome datasets were collected in human cancer. Therefore, a comprehensive cancer spatial transcriptomics resource that interactively visualizes and analyzes the spatial transcriptome data is needed.</p>
    <p>To address these challenges, we developed the spatial omics resource in cancer (SORC), an integrated platform that interactively visualizes the morphological feature of each tumor tissue slice and provides predicted cell types for each spot based on corresponding scRNA-seq data. We manually curated 82 datasets for 17 types of cancer, encompassing 722 899 spots in 269 slices. Notably, we matched reference scRNA-seq data with the majority of spatial transcriptomics datasets. All data were processed into a unified format and are available in the database. Furthermore, SORC provides five primary analytical modules for each slice that meet the main requirements of spatial transcriptomics analysis. Users can easily query, browse, download and access the data and analysis results in a user-friendly manner.</p>
  </sec>
  <sec sec-type="materials|methods" id="SEC2">
    <title>Materials and methods</title>
    <sec id="SEC2-1">
      <title>Data collection</title>
      <p>We comprehensively collected the spatial transcriptomics data for human cancer through a large-scale search in Gene Expression Omnibus (<xref rid="B20" ref-type="bibr">20</xref>), Zenodo (<ext-link xlink:href="https://zenodo.org" ext-link-type="uri">https://zenodo.org</ext-link>), Figshare (<ext-link xlink:href="https://figshare.com" ext-link-type="uri">https://figshare.com</ext-link>) and 10× Genomics, using keywords such as ‘spatial transcriptomics’, ‘human’, ‘cancer’, ‘carcinoma’ and ‘adenocarcinoma’. This search also included recently published articles related to spatial transcriptome analysis. In total, 82 spatial transcriptomics datasets were collected, covering 17 types of cancer and including 722 899 spots within 269 slices. Moreover, we also obtained the available hematoxylin and eosin (H&amp;E) images from corresponding database or literature.</p>
      <p>The scRNA-seq data corresponding to these spatial transcriptomics datasets were directly downloaded. For those spatial transcriptomics datasets that did not have matched scRNA-seq data from the same sample, we collected high-quality scRNA-seq data of the same cancer type from ImmCluster (<xref rid="B21" ref-type="bibr">21</xref>). In total, this comprehensive collection and analysis involved over 334 000 cells and 46 cell types.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-2">
      <title>Processing and clustering the spatial transcriptome</title>
      <p>For each spatial transcriptomics dataset, we utilized the Seurat R package for further processing (<xref rid="B22" ref-type="bibr">22</xref>). We only retained the spots that overlapped tissue sections and removed low-quality spots with either a small or large number of genes for each slice. We employed regularized negative binomial regression (SC transform) (<xref rid="B23" ref-type="bibr">23</xref>) to normalize raw unique molecular identifier (UMI) counts and performed principal component analysis (PCA) for dimensionality reduction. For each slice, elbow plots were used to determine the optimal number of principal components for spot clustering by the Louvain algorithm (resolution = 1). We also used the UMAP algorithm to visualize the spot clusters. Marker genes of the clusters were identified using the ‘findAllMarkers’ algorithm with ‘min.pct = 0.25, logfc.threshold = 0.25’.</p>
      <p>For all scRNA-seq data, we used a similar process with the Seurat R package (<xref rid="B22" ref-type="bibr">22</xref>). Cells with a high percentage of total UMIs originating from mitochondrial RNAs and cells with low total UMI counts were filtered out. We also used the SC transform to normalize raw UMI counts. Next, we identified highly variable genes and performed PCA to cluster the cells.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-3">
      <title>Identification of cell types</title>
      <sec id="SEC2-3-1">
        <title>Identification of immune, epithelial and endothelial cells</title>
        <p>We manually recorded 275 canonical marker genes for 46 cell types from ImmCluster (<xref rid="B21" ref-type="bibr">21</xref>). Based on the markers outlined above, we used ScType (<xref rid="B24" ref-type="bibr">24</xref>), a fully automated and ultra-fast cell type identification method, to assign cell types to each cluster. Specifically, low-confidence cell type annotations, which were assigned as ‘unknown’ cell types, were those with a low ScType score (less than a quarter of the cells in a cluster).</p>
      </sec>
      <sec id="SEC2-3-2">
        <title>Identification of malignant cells</title>
        <p>We applied the infercnvpy (<ext-link xlink:href="https://github.com/icbi-lab/infercnvpy" ext-link-type="uri">https://github.com/icbi-lab/infercnvpy</ext-link>) to estimate single-cell copy number variation (CNV) profiles to identify malignant cells. We created a gene sorting file from the human CRCh38 (V43) assembly (<xref rid="B25" ref-type="bibr">25</xref>), which included the chromosomal start and end positions of genes. Endothelial cells and immune cells were used as reference cells to define a baseline of CNV estimates. We calculated the CNV scores by ‘cnv.tl.cnv_score’ and reclustered all cells. Finally, compared with the reference cells, subclusters with significantly higher CNV scores were defined as malignant cells [two-tailed Mann–Whitney <italic toggle="yes">U</italic> test, false discovery rate (FDR) &lt;0.05 and fold changes &gt;2).</p>
      </sec>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-4">
      <title>Cell type decomposition</title>
      <p>For each spot in tumor tissue slice, we used the robust cell type decomposition (RCTD) (<xref rid="B26" ref-type="bibr">26</xref>) for deconvolution analysis of cell types. We used the corresponding scRNA-seq dataset as reference and identified cell type-specific marker genes. Following the standard RCTD analysis pipeline on the spatial transcriptomics data, we obtained the probabilities of cell types for each spot in the tumor tissue slice.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-5">
      <title>Co-occurrence analysis</title>
      <p>We assessed cell type co-occurrence in slices based on the probability of cell types for each spatial spot. In particular, we calculated the cell type co-occurrence scores using all spots in a given slice by Pearson correlations. For any pair of cell type <italic toggle="yes">i</italic> and <italic toggle="yes">j</italic>, we first obtained the probabilities <inline-formula><tex-math id="M0001" notation="LaTeX">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
${S}_i = [ {{p}_{i1},{p}_{i2}, \ldots ,{p}_{in}} ]$\end{document}</tex-math></inline-formula> and <inline-formula><tex-math id="M0001a" notation="LaTeX">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
${S}_j = [ {{p}_{j1},{p}_{j2}, \ldots ,{p}_{jn}} ]{\mathrm{\ }}$\end{document}</tex-math></inline-formula> that each cell type observed across <italic toggle="yes">n</italic> spots. Next, the Pearson correlation coefficient <italic toggle="yes">R</italic> was calculated based on the following formula:</p>
      <disp-formula>
        <tex-math id="M0002" notation="LaTeX">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
\begin{equation*}R = \frac{{\mathop \sum \nolimits_{k = 1}^n \left( {{p}_{ik} - \overline {S}_i} \right)\left( {{p}_{jk} - \overline {S}_j} \right)}}{{\sqrt {\mathop \sum \nolimits_{k = 1}^n {{\left( {{p}_{ik} - \overline {S}_i} \right)}}^2} \sqrt {\mathop \sum \nolimits_{k = 1}^n {{\left( {{p}_{jk} - \overline {S}_j} \right)}}^2} }},\end{equation*}\end{document}</tex-math>
      </disp-formula>
      <p>where <inline-formula><tex-math id="M0003" notation="LaTeX">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
$\overline {S}_i = ({1}/{n})\mathop \sum \nolimits_{k = 1}^n {p}_{ik}$\end{document}</tex-math></inline-formula>, <inline-formula><tex-math id="M0004" notation="LaTeX">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
$\overline {S}_j = ({1}/{n})\mathop \sum \nolimits_{k = 1}^n {p}_{jk}$\end{document}</tex-math></inline-formula> and <italic toggle="yes">n</italic> is the number of spots in a given slice.</p>
      <p>Hierarchical clustering was used to cluster the correlation coefficient matrices, which further enhanced the analysis by grouping similar cell types together. All the significant correlations (FDR &lt; 0.05) were visualized in cell type pairwise heatmaps (<xref rid="B27" ref-type="bibr">27</xref>).</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-6">
      <title>Cell–cell communications</title>
      <p>To further explore the interactions between tumor cells and immune cells, we first collected ligand–receptor pairs from CellChatDB (<xref rid="B28" ref-type="bibr">28</xref>), CellTalkDB (<xref rid="B29" ref-type="bibr">29</xref>), ICELLNET (<xref rid="B30" ref-type="bibr">30</xref>), iTALK (<ext-link xlink:href="https://github.com/Coolgenome/iTALK" ext-link-type="uri">https://github.com/Coolgenome/iTALK</ext-link>), NicheNet (<xref rid="B31" ref-type="bibr">31</xref>), SingleCellSignalR (<xref rid="B32" ref-type="bibr">32</xref>) and recent studies (<xref rid="B33" ref-type="bibr">33</xref>,<xref rid="B34" ref-type="bibr">34</xref>). We used iTALK to investigate cell–cell communications with the union sets of ligand–receptor pairs and single-cell transcriptomes as input.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-7">
      <title>Spatially variable genes</title>
      <p>Identifying genes with differential spatial expression patterns across tissue slices is important for the analysis of cellular states at specific locations and inference of intercellular communication. Here, we used the function ‘FindSpatiallyVariableFeatures’ in Seurat to measure the complex expression patterns of genes. Finally, genes with significantly higher Moran’s <italic toggle="yes">I</italic> scores were defined as spatially variable genes (SVGs; FDR &lt; 0.05 and <italic toggle="yes">I</italic> &gt; 0).</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-8">
      <title>Functional analysis of immune cells co-occurring with tumor cells</title>
      <p>We employed the COSG (<xref rid="B35" ref-type="bibr">35</xref>), a method based on cosine similarity, to identify genes that were highly expressed specifically in immune cell types co-existing with tumor cells. We selected the top 100 most highly expressed genes for each immune cell type. To predict the functions of these cell types, we initially calculated the single sample gene set enrichment analysis scores for each cell (<xref rid="B36" ref-type="bibr">36</xref>). Gene Ontology (<xref rid="B37" ref-type="bibr">37</xref>), KEGG (<xref rid="B38" ref-type="bibr">38</xref>), immune signatures (<xref rid="B39" ref-type="bibr">39</xref>) and cellular states (<xref rid="B40" ref-type="bibr">40</xref>) were used. Additionally, we carried out a hypergeometric test to identify the functions significantly enriched based on the highly expressed genes. Functions with an FDR &lt; 0.05 were identified as significant.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC2-9">
      <title>Database construction</title>
      <p>SORC was built on a Linux server. The web services have been built using Apache (version 6.0). The front end of SORC is built with HTML5, JavaScript, CSS and jQuery that consists of Datatable, ECharts, plotly and D3 plugin. All data in SORC were stored and managed by MySQL (version 5.5.21). SORC has been tested on a number of popular web browsers, including the Google Chrome, Firefox and Apple Safari web browsers. No registration or login is required.</p>
    </sec>
  </sec>
  <sec id="SEC3">
    <title>Database content and usage</title>
    <sec id="SEC3-1">
      <title>Database overview</title>
      <p>SORC serves as a comprehensive and user-friendly platform for the analysis of spatial transcriptome data in human cancer, providing insights into the cell type-specific distribution within the TME (Figure <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">1A</xref>). Based on rigorous data collection and filtering, we have collected 269 tissue slices from 17 different cancer types across 82 datasets, encompassing over 722 899 spots (Figure <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">1B</xref>)—a volume significantly larger than other existing spatial databases (<xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary Table S1</xref>). SORC offers cell type deconvolution for each spot, supplemented with corresponding scRNA-seq references (Figure <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">1C</xref>). The detailed annotations for spatial slices and specific marker genes aid in dissecting the spatial expression patterns of diverse cell types. Notably, we have investigated the co-localization of immune and malignant cells for each slice and dataset, a feature that holds significant value for the analysis of human cancer mechanisms. SORC integrates several interactive modules (Figure <xref rid="F1" ref-type="fig">1A</xref>), presenting results in an easily digestible format of diagrams and tables. Users can effortlessly browse, search and download all available data.</p>
      <fig position="float" id="F1">
        <label>Figure 1.</label>
        <caption>
          <p>Overview of the design and statistics of SORC. (<bold>A</bold>) Data collection, construction and functional tools of the SORC resource. (<bold>B</bold>) Number of spatial transcriptomics datasets, slices and spots across cancer types. (<bold>C</bold>) Numbers of cells and cell types identified from scRNA-seq data across cancer types.</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="gkad820fig1" position="float"/>
      </fig>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC3-2">
      <title>User interface</title>
      <sec id="SEC3-2-1">
        <title>Data browse and search</title>
        <p>Users can browse through an extensive list of all spatial transcriptomics datasets or apply filters based on specific cancer types and spatial sequencing technologies. By clicking on the title or slice, users can access basic information, links to relevant articles and detailed analysis results. Additionally, users can conduct a large-scale screening by searching for any keyword of interest, or by clicking on the text link next to the human diagram to access related data (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2A</xref>).</p>
        <fig position="float" id="F2">
          <label>Figure 2.</label>
          <caption>
            <p>User interface of SORC database. (<bold>A</bold>) Data browsing and search pages allow users to obtain spatial transcriptomics data based on sequencing technology, journals, cancer type, cell type or gene. (<bold>B</bold>) Cell type annotation module shows cellular component and provides marker information in spatial transcriptomics and single-cell transcriptomics data. (<bold>C</bold>) Spatial variable gene module offers SVG information and shows the expression of selected gene in spatial transcriptomics clusters and cell types. (<bold>D</bold>) Co-occurrence module shows the spatial relevance between tumor cells and immune cells in tissue slices. (<bold>E</bold>) Functional analysis module offers the activity scores and enriched significance of immune cells co-occurring with tumor cells. (<bold>F</bold>) Cell–cell communication information between tumor cells and co-occurring immune cells based on the ligand–receptor pairs.</p>
          </caption>
          <graphic xlink:href="gkad820fig2" position="float"/>
        </fig>
      </sec>
      <sec id="SEC3-2-2">
        <title>Cell type annotation</title>
        <p>SORC offers cell type annotation for spatial spots within each dataset, which is a crucial step in analyzing the tissue localization of cells (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2B</xref>). By integrating the scRNA-seq reference data, we inferred the probability scores for each spot’s cell type using a deconvolution algorithm and the final definitions of cell types were defined based on the highest score or pre-existing biological knowledge. Notably, users can select spots in the slices arbitrarily using lasso tools on the tool page (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2B</xref>), allowing for the analysis of specific regions’ cell composition. Additionally, we have identified the marker genes that are specifically expressed in each spatial transcriptomics cluster. Users can examine the expression levels of genes of interest in spatial location and cell types. Moreover, the expression patterns of two spatial transcriptomics marker genes can be compared side by side in the same tissue section, providing a foundation for exploring the localization distinction of specific markers (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2B</xref>).</p>
      </sec>
      <sec id="SEC3-2-3">
        <title>Identification of SVGs</title>
        <p>The significant variations in gene transcriptional activity across different anatomical positions often suggest their specific cellular states and functions. Therefore, SORC provides a list of SVGs and their respective statistics, such as Moran’s <italic toggle="yes">I</italic> value, for each slice (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2C</xref>). Users can explore the relationship between SVGs and their spatial locations, and observe their expression levels in different regions and spatial transcriptome clusters (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2C</xref>). Simultaneously, we illustrated the expression levels of selected genes among different cell types in the corresponding scRNA-seq data. Moreover, to assess the expression patterns of SVGs, we provided the specifically enriched spatial transcriptome clusters and cell types for each gene. It is noteworthy that, unlike the markers of the spatial transcriptomics cluster, the expression of SVGs displays the overall variation in the entire slice, rather than specifically overexpressing in the spot cluster with similar expression levels.</p>
      </sec>
      <sec id="SEC3-2-4">
        <title>Co-occurrence between immune cells and tumor cells</title>
        <p>The spatial distribution of immune cells and tumor cells within the TME is closely intertwined, potentially enhancing the antitumor response of immune cells. SORC archives the probability scores of co-localizations between different cell types for each slice, calculated based on the cell types of spatial spots (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2D</xref>). Users can visually identify immune cells that are closely associated with tumor cell distribution via heatmaps (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2D</xref>). Furthermore, for these significantly co-located immune cells, we offered valuable subsequent analyses to assist researchers in understanding the role of immune cells in different regions.</p>
      </sec>
      <sec id="SEC3-2-5">
        <title>Functional analysis of immune cells co-occurring with tumor cells</title>
        <p>To investigate the roles of immune cells that co-localize with tumor cells during cancer progression, we offered various functional gene sets for analysis, such as Gene Ontology. Users can filter results based on specific cancers or cell types of interest. The outcomes of functional annotation were displayed in a chart format, which includes enriched significance, pathway activity and marker genes utilized (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2E</xref>). Through this module, users can identify the spatial location and potential functions of immune cells that significantly associated with tumor cells across tissue slices.</p>
      </sec>
      <sec id="SEC3-2-6">
        <title>Communications between co-occurring immune cells and tumor cells</title>
        <p>After identifying immune cells that are associated with tumor cells in a slice, we inferred the interactions between these cells. Users can examine the intensity of the interactions and the receptor–ligand pairs that mediated cell–cell interactions. The results were displayed in the form of tables and river plots (Figure <xref rid="F2" ref-type="fig">2F</xref>). The cell interaction results in this module can be utilized to investigate the crosstalk between spatially closely related cells and the potential mechanisms in different cancers.</p>
      </sec>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC3-3">
      <title>Case study</title>
      <p>Lung adenocarcinoma (LUAD), a prevalent subtype of human cancer globally, often results in drug resistance and diminished prognosis in patients with invasive adenocarcinoma (IAC) (<xref rid="B41" ref-type="bibr">41</xref>). We have collected the spatial transcriptomics data (<xref rid="B42" ref-type="bibr">42</xref>) and corresponding scRNA-seq data of two IAC patients (TD1, TD2) in SORC (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3A</xref>). Comprehensive analysis of the tissue slices confirmed the utility of SORC in studying the TME. Specifically, SORC annotated 8468 spots and grouped them into 28 clusters based on gene transcription levels. With the aid of scRNA-seq data, we assigned 18 cell types to spots for deconvolution (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3B</xref>). We also identified genes specifically active in each spatial transcriptomics cluster. Notably, TM4SF1, a marker gene for tumor cells located at the slice center, was significantly upregulated in clusters 0, 6, 7 and 11 (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3C</xref>), confirmed previous findings (<xref rid="B42" ref-type="bibr">42</xref>). Our SVG exploration also highlighted high expression of TM4SF1 in the slice center and tumor cells, validating the reliability of cluster markers and SVGs (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3D</xref>).</p>
      <fig position="float" id="F3">
        <label>Figure 3.</label>
        <caption>
          <p>Case study from patients of IAC stage of LUAD (LUAD-IAC) in SORC. (<bold>A</bold>) The basic information and spot distribution of two slices in LUAD-IAC. (<bold>B</bold>) The spatial transcriptomics atlas on the left depicts the spot clusters, and the bar plot on the right shows the cell type deconvolution for each spot. (<bold>C</bold>) Selected marker in TD1. The violin diagram shows the expression of marker gene TM4SF1 in each cluster. The spatial transcriptomics atlas on the right depicts the spatial distribution of clusters with TM4SF1 as a marker. (<bold>D</bold>) The expression of selected marker TM4SF1 as SVG in TD1. (<bold>E</bold>) Heatmap shows the co-occurrence of tumor cells and immune cells in TD1. (<bold>F</bold>) Functional analysis results of immune cells co-occurring with tumor cells in TD1. (<bold>G</bold>) Communications between tumor cells and immune cells predicted based on the expression of candidate ligand–receptor pairs in TD1.</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="gkad820fig3" position="float"/>
      </fig>
      <p>The co-occurrence analysis revealed a close association between T cytotoxic cells, Treg cells and tumor cells, indicative of their pivotal roles in tumor suppression and promotion (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3E</xref>). This observation was consistent with previous findings that Treg cells co-localize with cancer cells in IAC (<xref rid="B42" ref-type="bibr">42</xref>). Based on the functional analysis module, we detected high activity of pathways in immune cells co-located with tumors, including T-cell action, T-cell receptor signaling, natural killer (NK) cell-mediated cytotoxicity, interferon receptor, and antigen processing and presentation (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3F</xref>), all of which underscore the active role of tumor immunity.</p>
      <p>Lastly, cell–cell communication analysis revealed multiple ligand–receptor pairs mediating interactions between tumor cells and co-located immune cells. For instance, the interaction between tumor cells and mast cells was mediated by TGFB2, ACVR1 and ACVR1B (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3G</xref>), aligning with the TGF-β signaling-related interactions reported previously (<xref rid="B42" ref-type="bibr">42</xref>). We also observed interactions between tumor cells and NK cells mediated by TGFB1–TLR2 and TGFB1–VDR (Figure <xref rid="F3" ref-type="fig">3G</xref>), as mentioned by Zhu <italic toggle="yes">et al.</italic> (<xref rid="B42" ref-type="bibr">42</xref>). In summary, these findings support that SORC is a valuable resource for helping analyze the spatial features of cancer immunity.</p>
    </sec>
  </sec>
  <sec sec-type="conclusions" id="SEC4">
    <title>Conclusions and future development</title>
    <p>Herein, we presented SORC, a comprehensive spatial transcriptomics data resource in human cancer, which interactively visualizes the morphological feature of each tumor tissue slice. Moreover, SORC provides five major analytical modules that cover the primary requirements of spatial transcriptomics analysis, including the annotations of slice, identifying SVGs, co-occurrence of immune cells and tumor cells, functional analysis and cell–cell communications. When comparing SORC with public databases and web-based platforms [i.e. SpatialDB (<xref rid="B16" ref-type="bibr">16</xref>), Spacer (<xref rid="B17" ref-type="bibr">17</xref>), Aquila (<xref rid="B18" ref-type="bibr">18</xref>) and SODB (<xref rid="B19" ref-type="bibr">19</xref>)] for visualizing and storing spatial transcriptomics data, we found that SORC offers broader cancer coverage, more datasets, richer downstream analysis tools and a more user-friendly interactive interface (<xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary Tables S1 and S2</xref>).</p>
    <p>As the spatial transcriptomics techniques continue to develop, in the future, we will continue to update and integrate more datasets into SORC by (i) collecting more newly generated spatial transcriptomics data to update SORC, including the datasets generated by both next-generation sequencing-based and imaging-based technologies; (ii) expanding the tissue images, such as H&amp;E staining and expression information; and (iii) integrating additional analytical modules to provide a richer understanding of the spatial transcriptome. In summary, SORC database is a valuable resource for providing an unprecedented spatially resolved cellular map for cancer and identifies specific genes and functional pathways to better understand the TME.</p>
  </sec>
